description.narrative: Government and partners have enhanced capacity to deliver quality education for improved learning outcomes for children in elementary education, which contributes to Access To Quality Learning Opportunities, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Innovation, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Business and Key Business Stakeholders demonstrate growing willingness, commitment and resource allocation for protecting and promoting child rights in policy and practice by 2022

title.narrative: Government and partners have enhanced capacity to deliver quality education for improved learning outcomes for children inelementary education

description.narrative: 54 million children 3-8-year-old benefited from UNICEF supported the Ministry of Education national guidelines for foundational learning adopted across the country. Career guidance portal established in 15 states and CBSE benefitting 26.2 million students (50% girls). UNICEF developed life skills program with measurement tools for both elementary and secondary reached 151,487 adolescents 10-14 years (50% girls) and 1,236 teachers (41% female) in five states. ; Emotional well-being program reached 1.1 million adolescent students across four states. Life Skills digital learning content finalized in Hindi and Gujarati. Capacity building of 400 teachers on ‘Constructivist use of technology for teaching’ initiated. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:09/01/2022
